ce:section.ce:para:
The volatile organic compounds (VOCs) are high vapour pressure and low molecular mass compounds. They are fats evaporated at high temperatures. The source of these materials is oil recycling, petrochemical factors, gas-oil industries, paper recycling, car emission gas and so on. These compounds are the main poisons in water contamination and air pollution. The VOCs are also serious illness problems for humans, such as cancer, infectious, genetic and metabolic diseases [259–261]. The determination of VOCs at low concentrations is important in analytical chemistry. The sensing performance of 3D nanomaterials based on 3D transition metal oxides for VOCs was studied in several research works [260,262–265]. For example, Cho et al. [263] prepared the porosity-controlled 3D SnO2 for acetone sensing. Fig. 8
                            shows (a) representation of acetone detection mechanism of Pt-PH-SnO2 porous nanomaterial, (b) base resistances dense of Pt-PH-SnO2, PH-SnO2 and SnO2, porous nanomaterials, and (c) representations employing principal component analysis (PCA) of simulated gases (1–5 ppm) with dense Pt-PH-SnO2, PH-SnO2 and SnO2, porous nanomaterials [264]. The obtained results confirmed that.

                                 (i)

the selectivity of 3D SnO2 for acetone is high; (ii) the 5 ppm acetone was accurately detected by the 3D SnO2 (Rair/Rgas = 44.83);


                                 (ii)

the limit of detection is 200 ppb (Rair/Rgas = 1.34);


                                 (iii)

the 3D SnO2 was suggested as the super sensor in the real-time diagnosis of diabetes in exhaled breath analysis;


                                 (iv)

the four VOCs included ammonia, toluene, hydrogen sulfide and acetone were effectively sensed at one example without overlapping.

In the other research work [34], the 3D ZnO cagelike spheres and hexagonal prism nanocompounds were more sensitive to 100 ppm triethylamine at 260 °C, and its maximum detection was 213.3. It is also fast response and recovery. Porous flower-like 3D tin oxide (SnO2) nanostructure was synthesized in, confirming that:

                                 (i)

the formaldehyde and toluene are high sensitively detected by the porous flower-like 3D tin oxide (SnO2) nanostructure;


                                 (ii)

the sensing responses to 100 ppm of toluene and formaldehyde were 9.7 and 9.5, respectively;


                                 (iii)

the sensing properties of this material depend on its microstructure;


                                 (iv)

this material is also reversible and good response. (v) 3D tin oxide (SnO2) nanostructure can sense the following VOCs: ethanol, acetone, toluene, formaldehyde, benzene, n-butanol, methanol and ammonia.



                                             Pesticides sensing

Chemical pesticides are fungicides, herbicides and insecticides that are widely used in agriculture. Their vastly used is serious ecological problems. The soil and aquatic systems are contaminated by the disposal of pesticides. The fungicides, herbicides and insecticides are the reason for serious health problems such as cancer upon prolonged exposure, nervous system, and eye and skin-related diseases. Detecting chemical pesticides at low concentrations is an important issue in material and engineering sciences [266–272]. The 3D nanomaterials based on 3D transition metal oxides are innovative materials in pesticide sensing. Several 3D transition metal oxides were suggested as effective agents in pesticide sensing. For example, Zhao et al. [35] prepared the porous hierarchical peony-like cobalt-based bimetallic oxides nanomaterial and its sensing performance for Diptetex and Omethoate pesticides was studied. The micro-mesoporous feature of this material is mainly responsible for pesticide sensing. The following main results are drawn:

                                 (i)

the recovery time is (94.8–105.1%) is very low;


                                 (ii)

this 3D nanomaterial senses the Diptetex and Omethoate pesticides at low concentrations by the electrochemical methods;


                                 (iii)

the detection limit is 0.033 pm for Omethoate and 0.36 pM for Diptetex (S/N = 3);


                                 (iv)

wide detection of Omethoate and Diptetex were 4.69 × 10−13 – 4.69 × 10−7 M and 3.88 × 10−12 – 3.88 × 10−6 M, respectively.

Mady et al. [304] prepared the magnetic 3D γ-MnO2@ZnFe2O4/rGO nanohybrid by one-pot hydrothermal method and its catalytic effect for phenol degradation was studied. The following results are found in this research work:

                                 (i)

3D γ-MnO2@ZnFe2O4/rGO is good reusability and recyclability;


                                 (ii)

95% of the carbon content was mineralized in 3 h;


                                 (iii)

the phenol degradation was done within 30 min;

                                          (v)

this 3D material is more efficient in the phenol degradation through the veal large surface active area;


                                          (vi)

the one-pot hydrothermal method is more effective in the syntheses of 3D γ-MnO2@ZnFe2O4/rGO.

In modern times, pharmaceutical drugs are widely used in medicine. However, large amounts of pharmaceutical drugs are disposed to rivers, lakes, seas, oceans, and other water resource systems. As a result, the aquatic systems are polluted with pharmaceutical drugs. This pollution is a danger to fish, plants, animals and human health. This pollution is mainly responsible for the serious health problems of live organisms. Therefore, pharmaceutical drug residues are an important problem in wastewater management. Traditionally, the various methods named ozonation, chlorination and biological degradation were performed to remove drug residues from the wastewater. These methods are not effective and are high quality at low concentrations of drug residues. Currently, the scientist of material and engineering research suggested the following updated methods for removing the drug from the wastewater: visible light input, ultraviolet (UV), non-hazardous oxidants and inert catalyst. The 3D nanomaterials-based 3D transition metal oxides are new materials in drug residue removal from wastewater [40]. This is due to their high catalytically impacts and multifunctional properties in drug removal. For instance, Sevastaki et al. [312] synthesized the 3D TiO2-polystyrene nanomaterial for drug removal. This 3D material is suitable for practical real-life applications and a low-cost alternative route for fabricating large-scale photocatalysts in drug residue removal from wastewater. The obtained results confirmed (Fig. 10
                           ) that:

                                 I.

this method is cost-effective, environmentally friendly and recyclable in wastewater management;


                                 II.

the 3D TiO2-polystyrene nanomaterial is recyclable and reusable;


                                 III.

the3D TiO2-polystyrene nanomaterial effective photocatalysts in the paracetamol and acetaminophen degradation;


                                 IV.

this 3D material provides promising photocatalytic properties.


                                 V.

this material achieved its 60% efficiency for paracetamol degradation after three cycles of regeneration.
